\section{Experimental Setup}
\label{sec:experiments}

We evaluate TSCG through controlled experiments designed to measure its impact on both task accuracy and token efficiency across diverse task categories.

\subsection{Model and Configuration}

All experiments use \textbf{Claude Sonnet 4} (Anthropic, 2025) as the primary target model, accessed through the Anthropic API with default parameters (temperature 0 for deterministic outputs). We selected Claude Sonnet 4 as a representative state-of-the-art instruction-following model with a BPE-based tokenizer. To assess cross-model transferability, we extend the evaluation to three additional models: \textbf{GPT-4o} (OpenAI, model \texttt{gpt-4o-2024-11-20}), \textbf{GPT-5.2} (OpenAI, 2026), and \textbf{Gemini 2.5 Flash} (Google, 2026). We also attempted evaluation on \textbf{Gemini 2.5 Pro} (a ``thinking'' model), but it produced empty responses on TSCG-optimized prompts due to incompatibility with its extended reasoning token generation; these results are discussed as a limitation (\S\ref{sec:discussion}). The multi-model evaluation uses a provider abstraction layer with per-provider rate limiting and token budget tracking, enabling clean comparisons across API providers. We note that TSCG's principles are model-agnostic in design, though the specific token savings from TAS depend on the target tokenizer and format-sensitive annotations (e.g., \texttt{[ANSWER:type]}) may interact differently with each model's instruction-following training.

\subsection{Benchmark Design}

Our benchmark comprises \textbf{19 core test cases} spanning \textbf{seven categories} designed to exercise different aspects of prompt-model interaction, supplemented by 25 hard tests and 82 domain-specific tests described in \S\ref{sec:domain-benchmarks}. The core benchmark categories are:

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Factual} ($n=4$): Direct knowledge retrieval requiring precise answers.
    \item \textbf{Reasoning} ($n=4$): Multi-step logical inference and arithmetic.
    \item \textbf{Classification} ($n=2$): Categorical assignment with defined label sets.
    \item \textbf{Extraction} ($n=1$): Structured information retrieval from text.
    \item \textbf{OptFirst} ($n=3$): Tasks where output format constraints dominate correctness (tests CFL effectiveness).
    \item \textbf{Complex} ($n=2$): Tasks requiring simultaneous application of multiple capabilities.
    \item \textbf{NearDup} ($n=3$): Near-duplicate sensitivity tests with minimal semantic variation.
\end{enumerate}

Each test case includes: (i) a natural language prompt, (ii) the expected correct output, (iii) an automated correctness checker, and (iv) category and difficulty labels.

\subsection{Strategies Evaluated}

We evaluate \textbf{six prompting strategies}:

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Natural}: The original natural language prompt, unmodified.
    \item \textbf{TSCG}: Full TSCG optimization using the \texttt{full} profile (all 8 principles active).
    \item \textbf{TSCG+SAD}: TSCG optimization with Selective Anchor Duplication enabled ($k=4$ anchors).
    \item \textbf{CCP}: Natural prompt with Causal Closure Protocol appended (tests the closure principle in isolation).
    \item \textbf{Repetition}: The natural language prompt duplicated in full (the Leviathan method; controls for the recency effect that CCP exploits).
    \item \textbf{TSCG+Rep}: TSCG optimization combined with repetition (tests whether combining structural optimization with brute-force repetition yields additional benefits).
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Evaluation Protocol}

To account for variance in model responses, we conduct \textbf{11 independent runs} of the core benchmark suite on Claude Sonnet 4, plus one additional run on Claude Haiku 4.5 for cross-model comparison. Each core run evaluates all 19 test cases across all six strategies, for a total of $19 \times 6 \times 11 = 1{,}254$ individual evaluations on Sonnet 4, plus $19 \times 6 = 114$ evaluations on Haiku 4.5, yielding $1{,}368$ core API calls. Domain-specific benchmarks add $25 \times 3 + 30 \times 3 + 22 \times 3 + 30 \times 3 = 321$ additional evaluations (three strategies per test across four phases), bringing the total to $1{,}689$ API calls for v1.0.0. The v1.1.0 clean re-runs add $82 \times 3 = 246$ Claude Sonnet 4 domain evaluations. The multi-model evaluation adds $44 \times 3 = 132$ evaluations each for GPT-4o, GPT-5.2, and Gemini 2.5 Flash (RAG + Tool Use phases, three strategies), totaling $132 \times 3 = 396$ additional cross-model evaluations, for a combined total of $2{,}331$ API calls across all versions and models.

\textbf{Metrics:}
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Accuracy}: Binary correctness per test case, aggregated as percentage across the benchmark.
    \item \textbf{Token count}: Number of input tokens consumed by the optimized prompt, as reported by the model's tokenizer.
    \item \textbf{Compression ratio}: $1 - (|\tok(\text{optimized})| / |\tok(\text{original})|)$, expressed as a percentage reduction.
    \item \textbf{Standard deviation}: Computed across the 11 independent runs to characterize run-to-run variance.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Baselines and Controls}

The \textbf{Natural} strategy serves as the primary baseline, representing the performance achievable with standard prompt engineering practices. The \textbf{Repetition} strategy controls for the recency effect that CCP exploits---if simple repetition achieves the same benefit as CCP, then CCP's structured approach adds no value. The \textbf{CCP} strategy tests whether the causal closure principle alone (appended to natural language) provides benefit without full TSCG optimization. The \textbf{TSCG+Rep} strategy tests whether combining structural optimization with brute-force repetition yields additional benefits beyond either approach alone.

\subsection{Reproducibility}

All experiments use temperature 0 for deterministic model outputs. The TSCG transforms are themselves deterministic, ensuring that the same input prompt always produces the same optimized output. The complete benchmark suite, including all 19 core test cases, automated checkers, and the TSCG implementation, is provided as supplementary material. The benchmark runner executes 71 unit tests to verify implementation correctness before each benchmark run.

\subsection{Domain-Specific Benchmarks}
\label{sec:domain-benchmarks}

To evaluate TSCG beyond general-purpose prompts, we developed four additional benchmark phases targeting domains where prompt optimization has the highest practical impact.

\subsubsection{Phase 0: Hard Tests ($n=25$)}

The hard test suite extends the core benchmark with 25 more challenging tasks spanning five additional categories designed to stress-test TSCG under adversarial and edge-case conditions. These tests include longer prompts, more complex constraint combinations, and tasks where subtle phrasing differences affect correctness. Each test was run once with three strategies (Natural, TSCG, TSCG+SAD).

\subsubsection{Phase 1: Long-Context Needle-in-a-Haystack ($n=30$)}

The long-context benchmark evaluates TSCG on needle-in-a-haystack (NIAH) retrieval tasks, where a critical piece of information is embedded within large context windows (up to 100K tokens). These tests measure whether TSCG's attention-optimized representations improve the model's ability to locate and utilize information scattered across long documents. Three strategies are evaluated: Natural, TSCG, and TSCG+SAD. This phase additionally exercises the \emph{Attention-Density Compression (ADC)} transform, which compresses verbose context passages while preserving retrieval-critical anchors.

\subsubsection{Phase 2: Retrieval-Augmented Generation ($n=22$)}

The RAG benchmark tests TSCG's effectiveness when applied to retrieval-augmented generation pipelines, where retrieved document chunks are injected into the prompt alongside the user query. TSCG optimization is applied to both the system instructions and the retrieved context. This phase exercises the \emph{Iterative Chain-of-Thought (ICoT)} transform, which restructures multi-hop reasoning prompts to align retrieved evidence with causal attention flow.

\subsubsection{Phase 3: Tool Use ($n=30$)}

The tool-use benchmark evaluates TSCG's impact on tool-description optimization, where the model must select and invoke the correct tool from a set of function definitions embedded in the system prompt. Tool descriptions are a particularly promising target for TSCG because they are highly structured, repetitive across calls, and consume substantial token budgets in production deployments. This phase exercises the \emph{Tool-Prompt Distillation (TPD)} transform, which compresses verbose tool schemas into token-efficient representations while preserving parameter semantics and invocation signatures.

\subsubsection{Domain Benchmark Protocol}

All domain-specific benchmarks were conducted as single-run evaluations (1 run per phase) due to the substantially higher cost of long-context and multi-tool API calls. The initial v1.0.0 evaluation of Phases 1--3 was significantly affected by API rate limiting during execution, which caused a substantial fraction of API calls to fail or return degraded responses across \emph{all} strategies. In v1.1.0, we re-ran the domain benchmarks with a custom rate limiter featuring token budget tracking (\S\ref{sec:deployment}), which eliminated rate-limiting failures entirely and produced clean results for all 82 domain-specific tests. We report both the original v1.0.0 rate-limited results and the v1.1.0 clean results, enabling direct comparison and demonstrating the impact of infrastructure reliability on benchmark outcomes.

\subsubsection{Multi-Model Evaluation Protocol}
\label{sec:multimodel-protocol}

To assess the cross-model transferability of TSCG's optimizations, we replicated the domain benchmark suite on \textbf{four models}: Claude Sonnet 4, \textbf{GPT-4o} (\texttt{gpt-4o-2024-11-20}), \textbf{GPT-5.2}, and \textbf{Gemini 2.5 Flash}. GPT-4o was evaluated on the full domain suite (Phases 1--3, $n=82$ tests, though NIAH results were not available for cross-model comparison); GPT-5.2 and Gemini 2.5 Flash were evaluated on RAG ($n=22$) and Tool Use ($n=30$) phases ($n=44$ tests per model, excluding NIAH). All models used the same test cases, correctness checkers, and evaluation protocol. The provider abstraction layer applies identical TSCG transforms to the prompts regardless of the target model, with only the API transport layer differing. This design isolates the effect of model architecture and instruction-following training from the prompt optimization itself. Three strategies were evaluated per model: Natural, TSCG, and TSCG+SAD. We additionally attempted evaluation on \textbf{Gemini 2.5 Pro} (a thinking model with extended chain-of-thought), but it produced empty responses on all TSCG-optimized prompts, requiring separate thinking-mode API handling not implemented in the current framework.

\subsubsection{LLMLingua-2 Comparison ($n=30$)}
\label{sec:llmlingua-comparison}

To address the question of how TSCG compares to statistical prompt compression methods, we conducted a controlled comparison with LLMLingua-2~\cite{pan2024llmlingua2} on the Tool Use benchmark ($n=30$). LLMLingua-2 uses a fine-tuned XLM-RoBERTa-large encoder to score token importance and prune low-information tokens at a target compression ratio. We evaluate four conditions: (A)~Natural baseline (uncompressed), (B)~TSCG-only (structural compression), (C)~LLMLingua-2 only (statistical compression at 50\% retention), and (D)~TSCG+LLMLingua-2 (sequential pipeline: TSCG first, then LLMLingua-2 at 50\% retention on the TSCG output). All conditions are evaluated on Claude Sonnet 4 with the same correctness checkers.

